When an OAuth2 signature algorithm like HMAC-SHA256 is compromised, the client (e.g., a mobile app) needs to seamlessly switch to a new algorithm like HMAC-SHA384 without disrupting the authorization flow. This is achieved by updating the `signatureAlgorithm` parameter in the client's `token request`. For instance, a Node.js client can use the `oauth2-client` library to update the algorithm as follows: 
```typescript
const { Client, JWT } = require('oauth2-client');

const client = new Client({
  clientId: 'your_client_id',
  clientSecret: 'your_client_secret',
  tokenEndpoint: 'https://example.com/token'
});

// Update signature algorithm to HMAC-SHA384
client.update({ signatureAlgorithm: 'HS384' });

client.tokenRequest({ grantType: 'password', username: 'your_username', password: 'your_password' });

When using OpenID Connect (OIDC) with oauth2, you'll encounter two types of tokens: ID tokens and access tokens. ID tokens contain user information and are signed with the client's secret key. Access tokens, on the other hand, grant access to protected resources. The userinfo endpoint provides an efficient way to retrieve user information from the ID token without requiring the client to store or manage user data. To use the userinfo endpoint, append the client ID and the ID token to the userinfo endpoint URL, as shown below.

const idToken = 'your_id_token_here';
const clientId = 'your_client_id_here';
const userinfoEndpoint = 'https://your-authority/oauth2/v2.0/userinfo';

fetch(`${userinfoEndpoint}?client_id=${clientId}&id_token=${idToken}`)
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data))
